This is *such* a good question, and I'm very glad you asked it!  

Opentensor (the Foundation) is basically building the infrastructure -- or, rather, the protocol, as to how the whole network functions.  How to incentivize the intelligence of models (via validation and token rewards), how to query and rank the responses of miners (AI models).

The subnet-owners are now coming in and devoting attention to specific functions: for example, subnet 5 is for image-generation (but there could theoretically be more than one subnet for these).  This allows the software to be laser-focused on a specific kind of AI-driven task (or provides some kind of support for the overall ecosystem, such as the scraping and storage subnets).

Then you have the third-party folks, who are building the front-ends that *do stuff* with the network that ordinary end-users (people who want AI-generated products) can use.  That would be people like Taostats.io, Tao.Studio, Chat with Hal, and so forth.

Well, OpenAI has its own proprietary thing.  Which is, I suppose, great.  But the huge difference is that Bittensor is incentivized competition amongst much more diverse (imo, ymmv) group of minds.  If you're familiar at all with SETI@home, this is more like that (only SETI@home wasn't incentivized).  Overall, in aggregate, it can bring a whole lot more power to bear on the problem than even a very large company is likely to be able to do (in time, at least).

no, miners provide the service and validators query/evaluate the miners

Validators are also the entry points, or gateways, into the network.  When a third-party application (Chat with Hal, for example) is querying the network, it's doing so through a validator.  The miners are the AI-models that are competing to provide the best response.

It varies depending on what you're doing; the subnets all have different codebases and thus different requirements with regards to the validator software.  As for running an AI-model: it will depend on the model (and which model you choose will be determined by which subnet you're in, for a given value of subnet -- some subnets, like storage, aren't operating like the ones that, say, do image generation).  For those subnets that require the miners to be AI models that provide responses, it's important to have enough of a background to be able to fine-tune your model: a pre-trained model will get you in the door, but you'll need to fine-tune it to remain competitive (Bittensor mining is not at all like hashrate mining).

I know it's kind of a fuzzy and vague answer, but honestly, there is no simple guide or easy answer.  If you're interested, you'll need to start exploring the subnets and see what they do and what's possible (and therefore, what's required).

We *do* have a testnet, but unfortunately the faucet's down right now. Splendid! One more thing and I will leave you in peace, are the tokens at risk if the wrong validator is chosen or there is no such thing?

No, the staked tokens never actually leave your wallet -- so long as you use "Stake" and not "Send" (sometimes people mistakenly use "send", in which case you have to track down the operator of the validator and hope they'll send you your tokens back).

But provided that you're staking, the validator does not have access to your staked Tao and cannot take them, even if operating maliciously: your Tao is never forfeited nor are the additional gains you receive in the form of Tao at a rate of 82% of that validator’s rate. 

If the validator goes down, both you and the validator stop earning Tao. At that point, you can unstake your Tao (including any gains you earned while validator was running) and the validator keeps their portion of the additional gains from your your Tao (18%).  Your original stake and rewards earned are never in jeopardy and can be unstaked at any time. 

I don't think you can actually stake to a key that isn't a validator.  Even if you could, though, essentially nothing would happen.

There is no unbonding period, so you can unstake at any time (in the Bittensor wallet, you go to "Stake" again, enter the key of the validator, click "Continue", and then you'll have the option to unstake).
